Query 1 : Product Performance

🔍 What this SQL is doing
Creates a master view that calculates profitability at the individual product level for every order. Transforms raw sales data into format suitable for manipulation and further analysis in Tableau.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated
. Calculated fields
. Complex business logic
. Working with relational databases (orders, items, products, and customers) 
. Optimised view for Tableau

CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW [dbo.vw_product_performance] AS

SELECT
    o.order_id,
    o.customer_id,
    o.order_date,
    o.order_status,
    oi.product_id,
    oi.quantity,
    oi.unit_price AS item_price,
    oi.unit_cost AS item_cost,
    oi.item_discount,
    oi.item_returned,
    p.category,
    p.brand,
    p.avg_rating,
    p.product_name,

    ---- Order Item Level calcs 

    (oi.quantity * oi.unit_price) AS gross_order_item_revenue,
    (oi.quantity * oi.unit_cost)  AS gross_order_item_cost,
    (oi.quantity * oi.unit_price) - (oi.item_discount * oi.quantity) AS net_order_item_revenue,
   
    CASE
        WHEN oi.item_returned = 1 THEN 0
        ELSE (oi.quantity * oi.unit_price)
             - (oi.item_discount * oi.quantity)
             - (oi.quantity * oi.unit_cost)
    END AS net_order_item_margin,

    ---- Returned flag

    CASE
        WHEN oi.item_returned = 1 THEN 1 
        ELSE 0
    END AS returned_item_flag

FROM orders o
INNER JOIN order_items oi
    ON o.order_id = oi.order_id
INNER JOIN products p
    ON p.product_id = oi.product_id
INNER JOIN customers c
    ON o.customer_id = c.customer_id;


Query 2 : Discount Sensitivity

🔍 What this SQL is doing
This query evaluates the discount sensitivity of every product in the catalog. It calculates the split between full-price and discounted sales for both volume and revenue, and then automatically flags products as "Discount Dependent" or "Full Price" based on how often they require a promotion to sell. 

🎯 Skills Demonstrated
. Diagnostic modeling through creating custom categorisation tiers based on sales ratios. 
. Use of defensive programming
. Precision rounding

SELECT
    category,
    product_name,
    ROUND(AVG(item_cost), 2) AS item_cost,
    ROUND(AVG(item_price), 2) AS item_price,
    ROUND(AVG(item_discount), 2) AS avg_discount,

    ---- Volume split

    SUM(CASE
        WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity
        ELSE 0
    END) AS quantity_discounted,

    SUM(CASE
        WHEN item_discount = 0 OR item_discount IS NULL THEN quantity
        ELSE 0
    END) AS quantity_not_discounted,

    SUM(quantity) AS total_quantity_sold,
    ROUND(SUM(item_discount * quantity), 2) AS total_discount,

    ---- Revenue split

    ROUND(SUM(CASE
        WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN net_order_item_revenue
        ELSE 0
    END), 2) AS revenue_discounted,

    ROUND(SUM(CASE
        WHEN item_discount = 0 OR item_discount IS NULL THEN net_order_item_revenue
        ELSE 0
    END), 2) AS revenue_not_discounted,

    ROUND(SUM(net_order_item_revenue - gross_order_item_cost), 2) AS total_margin,

    ---- Diagnostic metrics

    ROUND(1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
        / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0), 2) AS pct_volume_discounted,

    CASE
        WHEN 1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
             / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) >= 0.7 
             THEN 'Discount Dependent'

        WHEN 1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
             / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) >= 0.5 
             AND 1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
             / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) < 0.7 
             THEN 'Promotion Led'

        WHEN 1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
             / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) > 0.3 
             AND 1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
             / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) < 0.5 
             THEN 'Promotion Responsive'

        WHEN 1.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN item_discount > 0 THEN quantity ELSE 0 END)
             / NULLIF(SUM(quantity), 0) <= 0.3 
             THEN 'Full Price Product'
    END AS discount_dependency_flag

FROM dbo.vw_category_performance
WHERE order_date >= '2023-06-01'
  AND order_date <  '2024-06-01'

GROUP BY
    category,
    product_name

ORDER BY
    discount_dependency_flag DESC;


Query 3 : Volumes and Revenue from Loss-Making Products

🔍 What this SQL is doing

The following query isolates every transaction over the last year to determine exactly how many products were sold for a loss versus a profit. It separates the total profit generated by successful sales from the total "leakage" caused by loss-making items, providing a clear picture of how much money is being lost to aggressive discounting.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated

. Data modeling 
. Conditional logic to separate profitable sales from loss-making ones in a single, efficient step. 
. Common Table Expression (CTE)

WITH order_profitability AS (
    SELECT
        order_id,
        category,
        product_name,

        -- Quantity sold at a loss
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue < gross_order_item_cost THEN quantity
            ELSE 0
        END) AS quantity_loss,

        -- Quantity sold at a profit
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue >= gross_order_item_cost THEN quantity
            ELSE 0
        END) AS quantity_gain,

        -- Net loss from items sold at a loss
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue < gross_order_item_cost 
            THEN net_order_item_revenue - gross_order_item_cost
            ELSE 0
        END) * -1.0 AS loss,

        -- Profit from profitable items
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue >= gross_order_item_cost 
            THEN net_order_item_revenue - gross_order_item_cost
            ELSE 0
        END) AS gains

    FROM dbo.vw_category_performance
    WHERE order_date >= '2023-06-01'
      AND order_date <  '2024-06-01'
    GROUP BY
        order_id,
        category,
        product_name
)

Query 4 : Returns Investigation

🔍 What this SQL is doing
This query creates a high-level summary of every order to help the business understand why returns happen. It automatically categorises orders as "Full," "Partial," or "No Return," identifies if a customer is shopping for the first time, and groups orders into "Low," "Average," or "High" value buckets based on their final spend.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated
. Window Functions (OVER PARTITION BY) to pinpoint specific customer milestones
. Data architecture skills - joining multiple tables and using  conditional logic to transform raw numbers into strategic categories like "Discount Level" and "Return Status."

CREATE VIEW vw_order_level_returns AS

SELECT 
    ---- Core info

    o.order_id,
    CASE 
        WHEN SUM(item_returned) = 0 THEN 'No Returns'
        WHEN SUM(item_returned) = COUNT(o.order_id) THEN 'Fully Returned'
        ELSE 'Partially Returned'
    END AS order_return_status,

    ---- Customer info

    o.customer_id,
    CASE
        WHEN order_date = MIN(order_date) OVER (PARTITION BY o.customer_id) THEN 1
        ELSE 0
    END AS customers_first_order,
    acquisition_channel,
    country,
    device_type,

    ---- Order info

    channel,
    order_date,
    payment_method,
    CASE 
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) = 0 THEN 'None'
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) >= 0.2 THEN 'High'
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) >= 0.1 
             AND SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) < 0.2 THEN 'Average'
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) < 0.1 THEN 'Low'
    END AS discount_applied,

    CASE 
        WHEN (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) < 280 THEN 'Low'
        WHEN (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) >= 280 
             AND (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) < 840 THEN 'Average'
        WHEN (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) >= 840 THEN 'High'
    END AS order_value

FROM orders o
INNER JOIN order_items oi ON o.order_id = oi.order_id
INNER JOIN products p ON p.product_id = oi.product_id
INNER JOIN customers c ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id

GROUP BY 
    o.order_id,
    o.customer_id,
    order_date,
    acquisition_channel,
    country,
    device_type,
    channel,
    payment_method
